---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
import SoftmaxInspector from '../../components/interactive/SoftmaxInspector';
---

<BaseLayout title="The Output Head Produces One Logit Per Vocabulary Entry">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L11" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What is a logit?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        After all transformer layers have run, the model has a final hidden state for the last token position.
        This hidden state needs to become a prediction: which token comes next?
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>output head</strong> is one final linear projection. It takes the hidden state (dimension <code>d_model</code>) and projects it to a vector of size <code>|V|</code> — one score per vocabulary entry. Why a linear projection? Because it is the simplest operation that can transform a d_model-dimensional representation into |V| scores. The transformer layers have already done the hard work of building a rich representation; the output head just needs to map that representation into vocabulary space. A matrix multiply is sufficient, and keeping it simple avoids adding parameters that would be expensive to store and compute for the large |V| dimension.
      </p>
      <p>
        These raw scores are called <strong>logits</strong>. They can be any real number: positive, negative, or zero. A larger logit means the model considers that token more likely — but logits are not yet probabilities.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Interactive — Softmax Inspector</div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
        Adjust the logit values and see how they relate to the bar chart. In the next lesson you will learn softmax — for now, focus on the left side (logits).
      </p>
      <SoftmaxInspector client:load />
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          After processing "The cat sat", the output head produces logits like:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: auto 1fr; gap: 8px 16px;">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">"on"</span><span style="color: var(--sem-logits);">5.4</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">"the"</span><span>2.1</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">"a"</span><span>0.8</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">"dog"</span><span>1.2</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">"."</span><span>-0.3</span>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">... (|V| total scores)</span><span></span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          "on" has the highest logit (5.4), so it is the most preferred next token. But 5.4 is not a probability — it is a raw score.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Final hidden state: [d_model]</div>
        <div>Output head weight: [d_model, |V|]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-logits); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Logits: [|V|] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">one score per vocabulary entry</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-logits);">z = h &middot; W_out</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">z &isin; &reals;^|V| &nbsp; (logits are unbounded real numbers)</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The output head is a single matrix multiply. In many models, the output weight matrix is the same as the embedding table (weight tying). In <code>llama.cpp</code>, this projection is the last operation in the computation graph.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The output projection is [d_model, |V|] — a large matrix multiply. With |V| = 128,000 and d_model = 4096, this is a significant fraction of per-token compute. Larger vocabularies make this step more expensive.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">What Logits Cannot Do Yet</div>
      <p>
        Logits are raw scores. They can be any real number — positive, negative, very large, very small. You cannot interpret them as probabilities: a logit of 5.1 does not mean "51% chance." Raw logits are only directly meaningful relative to other logits at the same position of the same model — their absolute magnitudes do not have a universal scale.
      </p>
      <p>
        The next lesson introduces softmax, which turns one position's raw logits into a proper probability distribution that sums to 1. That is the specific problem softmax solves.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L11"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L11-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Given logits [3.2, 1.0, 5.1, -0.5], which token index is most preferred?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Index 0 (logit 3.2)', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Index 2 (logit 5.1)', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Index 3 (logit -0.5)', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The highest logit (5.1 at index 2) indicates the most preferred token. Larger logit = more preferred.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
